From Smith Subject Re Why is telephone audio Hz telephone systems have the capability of a passband of to The reason they do not implement this is It is not backward compatable to every telephone In addition the most effecent mix of electrical effecency and intelegability closly mateches a Close but no banana to paraphrase Garfield The reason Hz is used is that voice channels used to occupy bands when multiplexed on a trunk Therefore at the bottom and at the top of this band were filtered to minimise interference with the next Nowadays digital trunks have made this less relevant but the phone companies still see no reason to improve quality especially for free Therefore digital chunk of a trunk segments still have a guaranteed bandwidth of only so they can carry the equivalent of one analog line at the clock rate of a standard PCM or digital It's all Here in the UK the bandwidth restriction apparently only apply to local ie those used by the average domestic Private lines which are run from the local exchange to the leasing client are usually capable of a higher bandwidth if the exchange is Don't quote me on But I think I remember a BT engineer saying something to that effect when I was doing some work shadowing a few years Byeeeee Chris Name Mr Chris Smith Twang on that 'ole guitar Addrs Uni Liverpool University Quest To build more and more hardware Dgree Computer Science What ever the sun may be it is certainly not a ball of flaming gas All views expressed are my own and reflect that of private